The superstitious respect so generally entertained for the X family must, therefore, in the face of the evidence just presented, be abandoned. The Y family, albeit it has suffered at the hands of learned and unlearned scribes, represents as a body the purer tradition, although some of its individual members may be in a number of instances less trustworthy guides than A, for B itself, or its prototypc, as wc have seen, was not only subjected to the conjectural revision of the learned Pontanus, but was subsequently
